Preheat your oven to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7. Chop the @potatoes{400%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Pop the chunks onto a lined #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste} then toss to coat. Spread out in a single layer.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{25-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

Meanwhile, roughly chop the @chives{10%g}(roughly chopped) (use scissors if it's easier).

Zest half the @lemon{1/2}(zested and cut into thick wedges). Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a garlic press).

Chop the @broccoli{1}(chopped into florets) into florets (like small trees). Halve any large florets.

Place the broccoli on another lined baking tray. Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, season with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}, then toss to coat.

When the potatoes have been in the oven for ~{15-20%minutes}, pop the broccoli onto the middle shelf.

Roast until the edges are crispy and slightly charred, ~{10-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, place a large #pan on medium-high heat with @butter{1%tbsp} and a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Season @haddock{250%g} with @salt{to taste} and @pepper{to taste}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw fish.

Once butter is melted carefully place the haddock into the pan skin-side down.

Cook for ~{3-4%minutes} then cook for ~{2-3%minutes} on the other side.

> TIP: To get crispy skin on the fish, don't move it around when it's cooking skin-side down.

Add the chives and garlic to the pan and squeeze in the juice of half the lemon (double for 4p).

Continuously spoon the butter over the fish for ~{1-2%minutes}, then remove from the heat.

> IMPORTANT: The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

When cooked, plate up the haddock with the roasted broccoli and potatoes alongside.

Spoon the melted butter from the pan over the fish and sprinkle with the lemon zest to finish.

Serve the remaining lemon wedges alongside for squeezing over.